        '[EioxcXxcKK8NAImsdtdSg]:prompt "Prompt"':
          data:
            enableFunctionCall: false
            promptText: "You will receive a text chunk extracted from a PDF financial
              report.\r

              \  The extraction process is imperfect: charts and
              tables appear as\r

              \  fragments of numbers, dates, and labels mixed
              into the text. \r

              \  Your task: remove all chart and table data,
              keeping only analytical
              prose.                                                              \
              \r

              \  \r

              \  ---\r

              \r

              \  SECTION TITLES — ALWAYS KEEP:\r

              \r

              \  Section titles introduce major topics and must
              never be removed, even when they appear immediately before or
              after a chart block.\r

              \r

              \  A section title matches this pattern:\r

              \    Topic – Subtitle\r

              \    (optional) Author name on the next line\r

              \r

              \  Examples to always keep:\r

              \    \"Global backdrop – Turbulence after a calmer
              January\"\r

              \    \"Activity – Additional signs of slowdown;
              intensity remains uncertain\"\r

              \    \"Public finance – Inflation to help achieve
              the target in 2025; debt dynamics remain a concern\"\r

              \    \"External Accounts – Short-term adjustment
              does not change our outlook\"\r

              \    \"Monetary Policy – Tight for long\"\r

              \r

              \  Recognition rule: a line is a section title if it
              contains \" – \"    \r

              \  (space, em dash, space) and begins with a
              capitalized word and does \r

              \  not end with a period. Author names on the line
              immediately after   \r

              \  are also kept, but their absence does not change
              the rule.\r

              \r

              \  ---\r

              \r

              \  WHAT TO REMOVE:\r

              \r

              \  1. **Table or chart title** — a short descriptive
              line naming a     \r

              \  chart or table, immediately before data rows.
              These do NOT contain \" – \"\r

              \     Examples: \"Recurring balance shows small
              progress in 2024\",      \r

              \     \"BRL recovers in 2025\", \"Non-earmarked
              credit lending. Real daily\r

              \     s.a.. 3MMA (BRL Mn)\"\r

              \r

              \  2. **Axis labels and subtitles** — lines
              describing units, scales, or data series \r

              \  Examples: \"(% of GDP)\", \"Confidence indexes
              s.a.. Jan22 = 100.\",\"USD Bn\", \"3MMA\"\r

              \r

              \  3. **Chart data rows** — sequences of isolated
              numbers, percentages, or dates that form the body of a chart or
              table\r

              \     Examples: \"1.8  1.2  -3.3  4.8  3.0\",
              \"Jan-22  Mar-22  May-22 Jul-22\", \"75.3  74.4  86.9  77.3\"\r

              \r

              \  4. **Legend labels** — short lines identifying
              data series\r

              \     Examples: \"Primary balance\", \"Recurring
              balance\", \"Households\",  \r

              \     \"Companies\", \"XP's forecast\"\r

              \r

              \  5. **Footnotes** — lines starting with * or †
              that annotate a chart \r

              \     or table\r

              \     Examples: \"* Soy, corn, oil and iron ore\"\r

              \r

              \  6. **The Source line** — every chart/table ends
              with a line beginning\r

              \     with \"Source:\" Remove it along with
              everything above it that belongs to that    \r

              \     data block.\r

              \r

              \  ---\r

              \r

              \  WHAT TO KEEP:\r

              \r

              \  - Section titles (see above — always keep)\r

              \  - Author names that follow section titles\r

              \  - Any sentence with a subject and verb that
              conveys analysis, forecast, or argument\r

              \  - Sentences that contain numbers but are written
              in prose form      \r

              \    KEEP: \"We estimate that GGGD/GDP will reach
              79.9% in 2025.\"       \r

              \    REMOVE: \"79.9  83.6  80  75  77.3\"\r

              \r

              \  ---\r

              \r

              \  RULES:\r

              \r

              \  - A single chunk may contain multiple chart/table
              blocks — remove each\r

              \  - When prose and chart data are interleaved, keep
              the prose sentences\r

              \  - If in doubt, keep the text — do not remove
              analytical content     \r

              \  - Collapse multiple consecutive blank lines into
              one\r

              \  - TABLE OF CONTENTS EXCEPTION: If every non-empty
              line of the chunk matches the section title pattern (Topic –
              Subtitle) and there is no analytical prose between them, the chunk
              is a table of contents —   return an empty string\r

              \  - Return only the cleaned text, no explanation\r

              \r

